For {= facility_project =}+ UK fitness, gym, leisure, wellness, sport-centre, health-club, hotel-gym, country-club, or comparable facility projects with source-stated public activity within {= target_period =}, cover the {= project_facet =} project facets listed below by supplying a source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL under each facet) that ties the same project to facet-specific public evidence.

The useful trail is public project evidence, not a buyer or supplier prospect list.

Project facets:
- `public_status`: a source-stated non-procurement project status, decision, milestone, funding, approval, planning step, consultation, completion, delay, handover, opening, closure, or comparable public project state.
- `fitness_leisure_scope`: the concrete gym, fitness, leisure, wellness, sport-centre, studio, pool, equipment, health-club, hotel-gym, country-club, or comparable facility/amenity scope of the project.
- `procurement_delivery_detail`: a concrete procurement route, award, supplier, contractor, development-partner, framework/call-off, operator delivery responsibility, maintenance contract, fit-out/installation role, or equipment/technology implementation relationship tied to the project.

The project should be specific enough to identify through a client/authority or operator, a facility/project name, and a UK locality. It should be a concrete capital project, redevelopment, refurbishment, facility-change programme, fit-out, equipment or technology implementation, maintenance/replacement programme, construction/planning proposal, project call-off, or rollout tied to identifiable UK facilities. Broad leisure operating or management contracts, generic service contracts, reusable framework/procurement notices, supplier policies, organization-wide procurement pages, and multi-site leisure estates count only when the page ties them to such a specific facility-change project, call-off, or rollout. Contact details, named procurement people, supplier rankings, bid strategy, legal or procurement advice, product-suitability conclusions, safety/compliance adequacy conclusions, investment advice, outreach material, and purchasing-intent claims are outside the task.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the same UK facility project through the submitted client/authority or operator, facility/project name, and locality.
- The page must state or visibly date source-stated public activity for the project within {= target_period =}; publication dates, approval dates, decision dates, award dates, consultation windows, completion/opening dates, and project-timeline milestones can all carry the period signal.
- The page should make its facet-appropriate source role visible. For `public_status`, it should read as a non-procurement project-status, decision, planning, funding, consultation, official project, authority/operator, owner, or credible project-state surface, not merely a tender, award, open-opportunity, closed-opportunity, or contract-lifecycle notice. For `fitness_leisure_scope`, it should visibly describe the in-scope facility, amenity, works, equipment, or implementation scope rather than only naming a category or contract title. For `procurement_delivery_detail`, it should read as a project-specific procurement notice, award, decision record, supplier or contractor case study, framework/call-off context, named development-partner page, equipment or technology implementation page naming the provider/installer/delivery relationship, fit-out page, maintenance-contract page, or comparable delivery surface rather than a generic framework, supplier, or organization policy page.
- The page should expose a focused finding clearly scoped to the named project and `project_facet`. For `public_status`, this means a concrete non-procurement project state or milestone. For `fitness_leisure_scope`, this means concrete facility, gym, leisure, wellness, sport, studio, pool, equipment, amenity, works, or implementation detail; title/category terms such as "outdoor gym", "sports facility", or "leisure operating contract" are not enough by themselves. For `procurement_delivery_detail`, this means a concrete procurement route, award, supplier, contractor, development partner, framework/call-off, operator delivery responsibility, provider/installer role, maintenance contract, or delivery relationship tied to the project. A funding statement, named equipment brand, technology feature, amenity list, or ordinary refurbishment-scope description is not enough unless the page also states the project-specific procurement or delivery relationship.
